---
import { Globe, Eye, Compass, Terminal } from "@lucide/astro";
import { slide } from "astro:transitions";
import BackRow from "../components/BackRow.astro";
import { siteConfig } from "../data/site";
import Layout from "../layouts/Layout.astro";

export const prerender = true;

const structuredData = [
  {
    "@type": "AboutPage",
    "@id": `${siteConfig.url}/about/#about`,
    url: `${siteConfig.url}/about/`,
    name: "About a9x",
    description:
      "A personal look at how a9x sees the world, what catches their attention, and how they spend their time.",
    mainEntity: {
      "@id": `${siteConfig.url}#person`,
    },
  },
];
---

<Layout
  title="about | a9x"
  description="A personal look at how a9x sees the world, what catches their attention, and how they spend their time."
  pageType="AboutPage"
  ogType="profile"
  structuredData={structuredData}
>
  <article
    class="page page--interior"
    transition:name="page"
    transition:animate={slide({ duration: "0.28s" })}
    tabindex="-1"
    data-page
  >
    <div class="page-header">
      <h1 class="page-title" transition:name="about-title">about</h1>
      <p class="page-subtitle">a little about how i see things</p>
    </div>

    <p class="about-opener" aria-hidden="true">
      this is probably the most honest page on this site.
    </p>

    <!-- Hero Quote -->
    <div class="about-hero-quote" aria-label="Opening quote">
      <div class="about-hero-quote__mark" aria-hidden="true">&ldquo;</div>
      <blockquote class="about-hero-quote__text">
        Even after all this time, the sun never says to the earth &lsquo;you owe
        me.&rsquo; Look what happens with a love like that — it lights the whole
        sky.
      </blockquote>
      <cite class="about-hero-quote__attribution">— Hafiz</cite>
    </div>

    <!-- Section 1: How I See the World -->
    <section class="about-section" aria-label="How I see the world">
      <div class="about-section__header">
        <span class="about-section__icon" aria-hidden="true"><Globe /></span>
        <h2 class="about-section__title">how i see the world</h2>
      </div>

      <div class="about-divider" aria-hidden="true">
        <span class="about-divider__line"></span>
      </div>

      <div class="about-section__body">
        <p>
          i grew up here in the united states, and i've watched enough to know
          we don't always live up to what we tell ourselves we are. there's a
          lot that's broken — not just here, but everywhere. systems that forget
          the people inside them, conversations turning into shouting matches
          before anyone listens.
        </p>
        <p>
          i've thought about it a lot, and i keep coming back to the same place:
          the only thing that has ever actually fixed anything in practice is
          when someone decides to understand someone else first.
        </p>

        <div class="about-callout">
          <span class="about-callout__bar" aria-hidden="true"></span>
          <p class="about-callout__text">
            not agreement. not compromise. just… seeing another person clearly,
            even when you disagree with everything they stand for. that changes
            something.
          </p>
        </div>

        <p>
          i don't think unity means pretending things are fine. i think it means
          caring enough to show up when it's hard. empathy isn't softness. it
          takes more out of you than anger ever does, but it's the only thing
          i've seen actually move the needle.
        </p>
        <p>
          so that's my baseline. the world is messy and full of contradictions,
          and i still choose to believe people are worth it. not because i'm
          optimistic, but because what's the alternative?
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Section 2: What Always Catches My Attention -->
    <section class="about-section" aria-label="What catches my attention">
      <div class="about-section__header">
        <span class="about-section__icon" aria-hidden="true"><Eye /></span>
        <h2 class="about-section__title">what always catches my attention</h2>
      </div>

      <div class="about-divider" aria-hidden="true">
        <span class="about-divider__line"></span>
      </div>

      <div class="about-section__body">
        <p>
          there's this thing that happens whenever i hear sirens. i don't just
          hear them — i notice them. i'll stop mid-sentence, look toward the
          sound, and somewhere in the back of my mind i'm already thinking about
          where they're headed and what happened. a structure fire? a medical
          call? someone just having the worst day of their life?
        </p>
        <p>
          i've been like that for as long as i can remember. something about
          public safety, about the people who drive toward the thing everyone
          else runs from, has always stuck with me. not in a hero-worship kind
          of way. more like — there are people out there right now, at 3am,
          making split-second decisions that change someone's entire future. and
          most of us just sleep through it.
        </p>

        <div class="about-inline-quote">
          <p>
            i think about that a lot. the weight of the things that happen while
            the rest of the world isn't watching.
          </p>
        </div>

        <p>
          aviation hits me in a similar way, but for completely different
          reasons. there's a moment right after takeoff — the wheels leave the
          ground, the noise changes, and everything below you gets small really
          fast. it's the closest thing to a reset button i've found. you're not
          in any city or any country. you're just… up there. it always makes the
          problems on the ground feel like they have edges, like they're
          containable. and for some reason that's incredibly calming.
        </p>
        <p>
          i can sit at a window seat and watch approach patterns for hours and
          not get bored. the way a plane turns final, lines up with a runway
          from miles out, and just commits. there's something honest about it.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Section 3: What I Spend My Time Doing -->
    <section class="about-section" aria-label="What I spend my time doing">
      <div class="about-section__header">
        <span class="about-section__icon" aria-hidden="true"><Compass /></span>
        <h2 class="about-section__title">what i spend my time doing</h2>
      </div>

      <div class="about-divider" aria-hidden="true">
        <span class="about-divider__line"></span>
      </div>

      <div class="about-section__body">
        <p>
          some weekends i'll drive out to places most people pretend don't
          exist. abandoned buildings, old factories, overgrown lots that used to
          be something. urbex — urban exploring — is hard to explain to people
          who haven't done it. it's not about the danger or the trespassing or
          the aesthetic instagram shots.
        </p>
        <p>
          it's about standing in a room where hundreds of people used to work or
          live or learn, and now it's just peeling paint and silence. there's a
          kind of honesty in decay. nothing is performing for you. it's just…
          what's left when everything else moves on.
        </p>

        <div class="about-callout">
          <span class="about-callout__bar" aria-hidden="true"></span>
          <p class="about-callout__text">
            i think that's why i keep going back. it reminds me that nothing is
            permanent, and that's not sad — it's just true.
          </p>
        </div>

        <p>
          the rest of the time, honestly, it's pretty simple. i like being
          around my friends. not doing anything specific — just existing in the
          same space. driving around at night with the windows down. sitting in
          someone's kitchen talking about something that doesn't matter at all
          and laughing until it hurts. the kind of time that doesn't make it
          into any story because nothing "happens," but it's the stuff i'd
          actually miss.
        </p>
        <p>
          i have this constant pull to go see things. not tourist destinations —
          just places. a road i haven't driven. a part of a city i've never
          walked through. i don't even need a reason. the point is just to go
          and be somewhere i haven't been, and let whatever's there surprise me.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Section 4: The Quiet Part -->
    <section class="about-section" aria-label="Skills and tools">
      <div class="about-section__header">
        <span class="about-section__icon" aria-hidden="true"><Terminal /></span>
        <h2 class="about-section__title">
          the same curiosity, different place
        </h2>
      </div>

      <div class="about-divider" aria-hidden="true">
        <span class="about-divider__line"></span>
      </div>

      <div class="about-section__body">
        <p>
          there's a part of my life that's a lot less poetic and a lot more
          "staring at a screen at 4am wondering why a function that worked five
          minutes ago suddenly doesn't." i write code. have for years. i'm good
          at it in the way where i don't really think about it anymore — it's
          just how i build things.
        </p>
        <p>
          and somewhere along the way, i got deep into the AI tooling side of
          things. not the hype cycle, not the takes on twitter. the actual
          practical stuff — using these tools to move faster, build better,
          solve problems i wouldn't have had the bandwidth for otherwise. it's
          changed how i work more than anything else in the last few years.
        </p>

        <div class="about-inline-quote">
          <p>
            but that's just what i do. it's not who i am. if you took the code
            away, i'd still be the same person staring at airplanes and
            exploring abandoned buildings.
          </p>
        </div>

        <p>
          i think the reason i even mention it is because it connects to
          everything else. the curiosity. the drive to understand systems —
          whether that's a web stack, an emergency response protocol, or why a
          building was left to rot. it's all the same muscle. i just want to
          know how things work, and then i want to make them work better.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <footer class="page-footer">
      <BackRow href="/" label="back" />
    </footer>
  </article>
</Layout>
